03906nam a22006015i 9780674033726DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740337267 a10.4159/97806740337262doi  a(DE-B1597)626020  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aEDU0150002bisacsh1 aO'Neil, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAcademic Freedom in the Wired World :bPolitical Extremism, Corporate Power, and the University /cRobert O'Neil. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Discovering Academic Freedom -- t2 Protecting Academic Freedom -- t3 The Constitution and the Courts -- t4 Academic Freedom in Times of Crisis -- t5 The Rights of Academic Researchers -- t6 Intersections of Academic and Artistic Freedom -- t7 New Technologies: Academic Freedom in Cyberspace -- t8 Whose Academic Freedom? -- t9 Bias, Balance, and Beyond: New Threats to Academic Freedom -- t10 Academic Freedom in Perspective -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this passionately argued overview, a longtime activist-scholar takes readers through the changing landscape of academic freedom. From the aftermath of September 11th to the new frontier of blogging, Robert O'Neil examines the tension between institutional and individual interests. Many cases boil down to a hotly contested question: who has the right to decide what is taught in the classroom? O'Neil shows how courts increasingly restrict professorial judgment, and how the feeble protection of what is posted on the Internet and written in email makes academics more vulnerable than ever. Even more provocatively, O'Neil argues, the newest threats to academic freedom come not from government, but from the private sector. Corporations increasingly sponsor and control university-based research, while self-appointed watchdogs systematically harass individual teachers on websites and blogs. Most troubling, these threats to academic freedom are nearly immune from legal recourse. Insisting that new concepts of academic freedom, and new strategies for maintaining it are needed, O'Neil urges academics to work together--and across rigid and simplistic divisions between "left" and "right."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067403372640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674033726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674033726/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK